==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} [[disgisen]], [[disguisen]], borrowed from {{etyl|fro}} [[desguiser]] (modern [[déguiser]]), itself derived from [[des-]] "[[dis-]]" (from {{etyl|la}} [[dis-]]) + [[guise]] "guise" (from a Germanic source).

===Pronunciation===
* ''General American'' {{IPA|/dɪˈskaɪz/}} {{SAMPA|/dI"skaIz/}}
* {{audio|En-us-disguise.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{hyphenation|dis|guise}}
* {{rhymes|aɪz}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An [[attire]] (e.g. [[clothing]]) used to [[hide]] one's [[identity]] or [[assume]] another.
#: ''That cape and mask complete his '''disguise'''
# {{figurative}} The [[appearance]] of something on the outside which masks what's beneath.
# The act of disguising, notably as a ploy
#: ''Any '''disguise''' may expose soldiers to be deemed enemy spies

